{
  "texts": [
    "The upshot is that, even though the action of N is not globally well-defined, there are well-defined transformation groupsN b ⊂ Diff(M b) of each fibre M b = π -1 (b)that act simply-transitively.",
    "These N b vary smoothly with b, in the sense that they come from transformation groups N U ⊂ Diff(M U).",
    "An isomorphism N b ≃ N depends of course on the choice of local trivialisation, and for different choices, two such isomorphisms differ by φ ij ∈ Aut(N).",
    "Definition 2.2.",
    "A tensor field on M is called invariant, if in local trivialisations U i × N the corresponding tensor is invariant under (6).Since the local actions yield a well-defined transformation group N Ui of M Ui = π -1 (U i) independent of the trivialisation, invariance is indeed well defined.From Definition 2.1 and the general theory of fibre bundles, any twisted principal bundle is associated to some (Aut(N) ⋉ N L)-principal bundle P → B, whose transition functions have locally constant Aut(N)component."
  ]
}